snippet.title: Migrant sex offender given £500 after threat to disrupt deportation | BBC News
snippet.description:
A migrant sex offender who was mistakenly released from prison was given a £500 payment after threatening to disrupt his deportation from the UK to Ethiopia, the BBC understands.
 
Hadush Kebatu was jailed after sexually assaulting a 14-year-old girl and a woman while living in an asylum hotel in Epping, Essex, but was mistakenly set free by prison staff on Friday and was brought back into custody following a two-day manhunt.
 
It is understood the payment was a decision made by the removal team, not ministers, and was considered as an alternative to a more expensive process.
 
Kebatu was not on the government's Facilitated Returns Scheme - for foreign national offenders who agree to leave the UK voluntarily - under which he would have been given £1,500.
 
Sources said the £500 payment avoided "a slower and more expensive process, which would have included detention, a new flight and potentially fighting subsequent legal claims".

snippet.title: Migrant sex offender deported from UK after mistaken release | BBC News
snippet.description:
A migrant sex offender who was mistakenly released from prison has been deported from the UK with no right to return.
 
Hadush Kebatu was jailed after sexually assaulting a 14-year-old girl and a woman in Epping, Essex, while living in an asylum hotel, but was mistakenly set free by prison staff on Friday. 
 
He was brought back into custody following a two-day manhunt.
 
"I have pulled every lever to deport Mr Kebatu and remove him off British soil. I am pleased to confirm this vile child sex offender has been deported”, said UK Home Secretary Shabana Mahmood.
 
Kebatu arrived in Ethiopia's capital Addis Ababs on Wednesday and was briefly held by officers at the airport, but was then released because there was "no legal basis for his continued detention", Ethiopian Federal Police spokesman Jaylan Abde said.

A strong performance in Athens could secure his place at the season finale.
Meanwhile, Novak Djokovic returns to action after Shanghai, but faces a potential early challenge from his 'bogeyman', Alejandro Tabilo. Tabilo is one of the few players with a perfect record against Djokovic, having beaten him twice. Will the Serbian legend overcome this hurdle?
With the season coming to a close, every match matters. Who will rise to the occasion in Athens?
